      notFull.wait();
    }

    // Add count items atomically
    for (int i = 0; i < count; i++) {
      buffer[rear] = data[i];
      rear = (rear + 1) % BUFFER_SIZE;
      this.count++;
    }

    notEmpty.signalAll(); // wake up waiting consumers
  }
```

The structure uses a circular buffer with front and rear pointers to track positions. When a producer adds items, it checks if there's sufficient space, then inserts each item and updates the rear pointer. After adding, it signals all waiting consumers that items are available.

The monitor's entry procedure mechanism ensures atomicity—multiple producers can't interleave their additions since only one can execute an entry at a time. This satisfies the requirement that items from the same producer must be added consecutively without interference from other producers.

The design uses a circular buffer with `count` tracking occupancy and `front`/`rear` indices. When a producer calls `AddToBuffer(data, itemCount)` where itemCount is 1 or 2, it first checks if there's sufficient space, waiting on `notFull` if the buffer would overflow.

